Run
5mi total w/3mi Steady State
Planned: 5 mi
1mi warmup
3mi Steady State on rolling hills
1mi cooldown

Taking this a step at a time-- I want to learn more about you as we build into workouts. Tabor is great for this. You're working in the effort I call Steady State (Zone 2, aerobic threshold) to challenge yourself while still remaining aerobic. The hills will naturally create some undulations in your effort, and that's by design as you'll get more comfortable running fast while still recovering when running downhill.

Run
Tempo: 4x5mins with 2mins jogging recovery
Planned: 7 mi
2mi wu
4x5mins at Tempo effort with 2mins jogging recovery
2mi cd

Tempo (threshold, Zone 3) is a notch up from the previous week's steady state. Think of this as an effort you can sustain for only about one hour. It should feel challenging but sustainable or "comfortably fast". Let's do this around the reservoir on 60th, but include the trail on the east side that leads up and back downhill between the staircase to the upper reservoir. This will do two things: create a mental/physical challenge on the climb but also give a chance to find rhythm on the flat section.

Run - Long Run
17mi long run
Planned: 17 mi
Again going for a good amount of vertical gain, 2500' is plenty.

One thing to really think about is what you're consuming on these runs. What's your general nutrition routine on long runs? For runs 90-120mins, have at least 200 calories during the run in the form of gels or liquid calories. For longer runs 2+ hrs, plan to eat 150-200cals per hour (might need to work up to 200cals).
Completed: 14.3 mi ~ 2:44:12 (11:28 min/mi)
Workout Comments:
5/2/2022 9:16 AM
Jon Schafer
Nutrition — I'm pretty good about this. I consume Clif gels (100c), x2 an hour (200c). And hydrate with Nuun. I talked to a sports nutritionist awhile back about what level of sodium I need to replace bc I sweat A LOT. Nuun works pretty well for me.  
 
I've just started to take in more calories — Arcellus lent me a few Spring during our E2E effort — and that not only tasted better, but gave me more energy. TL;DR I think I might need 300 per hour.

Run - Fartlek
3 sets of 6x30s hard/30s easy with 3mins rest between sets
Planned: 7 mi
2mi wu
6x30s hard/30s easy
3mins easy
6x30s hard/30s easy
3mins easy
6x30s hard/30s easy
2mi wu

These will be mostly similar to the 1min on/1min off reps from a few weeks ago, but note that 30s isn't a lot of rest, meaning you're going to start feeling it over the final 2-3 reps especially. By the ned you should be working pretty hard and huffing and pudding. These are a great way to improve V02max while still keeping the reps fairly short to break it into chunks.

Thursday, March 17, 2022
5:17 AM
Run - Hills
6-8 x The Shaft, alternate running and hiking
Planned: 7 mi
2mi wu
6-8x Mountain View Dr/71st hill climbs, alternating running and hiking
full recovery after each, walking or jogging back down
2mi cd

This is the steep climb just next to the big long 72nd climb on the east side of Tabor. One of the spicier climbs in the neighborhood! In high school we called it "The Shaft". Just do the steep part, not the entirety of the road. Do the first one running, the second one powerhiking fast, and alternate back and forth. The hope is that you're working pretty hard on each rep, but get plenty of recovery so you're fully ready for the next one. You should aim for 6 total hill climbs, and you can add a 7th and 8th if you're still feeling strong. Always finish a workout feeling like you could have done more. Let me know if you have questions about this one!

2mi cd

Less steep than the shaft, but that means consistent running. Start from the gate and run on the gravel to mimic trails a little more. Go by time and push the effort so you're feeling pretty spent after each climb. Take as much recovery as you need! Keep an eye on where you finish each 2min rep--if you're doing this right you actually should go slower and slower because you're gassed from the workout. Do 5, but continue to a 6th if you've got more in you (and don't spend yourself completely!--always finish a workout feeling like you could've done more)

Run - Tempo Run
3x3mins tempo, 10min uphill steady, 3x3mins tempo
Planned: 8 mi
1.5mi wu
3x3mins tempo with 1min rest
4mins easy
10min uphill steady
4mins easy
3x3mins tempo with 1min rest
1.5mi cd

You're pretty familiar with the shorter tempo reps, so really focus on the hill climb. The idea is to find a grade that still allows you to run the entire time. I like snaking my way up to the top of Tabor for this. Keep the climb steady but sustainable, and it's okey to hike asa long as you're keeping the effort even. For the rest period after the climb, you might need to take a little extra time to descend to a flat area for the final tempo reps.

Other - Notes
Hot Bath or Sauna
Totally optional, but a nice way to get a little altitude acclimatization prior to race day. Here's what it looks like:
Hot bath up to your neck or sauna until you feel uncomfortably hot, them remain in the sauna for an additional 5-10 minutes. Hydrate well the entire time. These training adaptations disappear quickly, so you'll need to do this close up to race day. 5 sessions should give you a nice boost. The most bang for your buck you can get is to do this directly after your run. You'll already have an elevated core temp at that time, so it won't take as long to get a heat stress in the sauna/hot bath
